# Portfolio project scan

**Audience for your written output:** business owners, operators, and buyers—not developers. They care about problems solved, time saved, money made, and day-to-day control—not frameworks, repos, or architecture.

**Your job (internal):** Still explore the full codebase (README, routes, admin/dashboard, payments, messaging, config, rules). Understand what is really built. Then **translate** into plain language. Never expose file paths, function names, or stack jargon in the copy fields unless the portfolio **Tech stack** line requires a short label.

**Style:** jot dots only. Short fragments. No paragraphs. No word cap on bullets. Skip empty sections. Write like a product brochure, not a README.

**Voice**
- Benefits and outcomes, not implementation (“Customers book online” not “Expo Router + RTDB listener”)
- Everyday words: bookings, orders, quotes, inbox, payments, reminders, dashboard, staff, customers
- Avoid: API, SDK, CRUD, schema, deploy pipeline, middleware, auth provider names (unless unavoidable in **Tech stack**)
- Admin section = what the **owner** can do without calling you

**Output** — use these labels exactly (copy-paste into portfolio Admin modal):

---

**Title:**  
**Filter category:** `professional` | `creative`  
**Live project URL:** *(from README/deploy config, or `ASK_USER`)*  
**Image alt:** *(short, plain, e.g. “Lawn care app booking screen”)*  

**Description:** *(one-line hook a non-tech owner gets, then bullets)*
- · who it’s for (type of business)
- · what customers can do on their own
- · what the business gains (less phone tag, fewer missed jobs, faster checkout, etc.)
- · standout features in plain English (as many dots as needed)

**Tech stack:** *(comma-separated; keep short—product words OK: “Mobile app”, “Web app”, “Online payments ready”, “Cloud database”. Add framework names only if clearly central, max 3–5 items)*  

**Outcome:** *(jot dots—business results)*
- · live / demo / in use with a client
- · real-world impact if known (more orders, less admin time, happier customers)
- · what’s ready today vs “coming soon” (say it simply)

**Detail modal — admin focus:** *(jot dots—owner/back-office wins only)*
- · what they see on login (orders, calendar, messages, settings, etc.)
- · what they can change without a developer
- · notifications, reports, or staff-friendly workflows
- · payments/invoicing in buyer terms (“take card payments”, “cash on delivery”, “send payment link”)

**Best for:** *(one type of business per line, 3–12—how they’d search for themselves)*
- · Lawn care companies
- · …

**Internal notes (optional, for you only—omit from modal paste):**
- · technical gaps / TODOs found in repo
- · entry files if you need a reminder

---

**Rules**
- `professional` = real client or production-ready business app; `creative` = demo, experiment, template
- If URL or screenshot unknown, write `ASK_USER`—don’t invent
- Don’t edit portfolio database from this task—output fields only
- When unsure, prefer “ASK_USER” over guessing metrics or pricing
